"1213":"1213","1169":"1169","1234":"1234","1211":"1211","of Chichester,, England":"Chichester, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Morpeth, Northumberland, England":"Morpeth, Northumberland, England","Chichester, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Chichester, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Morpeth, England":"Morpeth, Northumberland, England","Chichester, West Sussex, England":"Chichester, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rede","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Portuguese: habitational name from a place so named in Braga district (Portugal)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Rede was born in 1173, in Chichester, Sussex, England, his father, Brianus Derede, was 34 and his mother, Jane Baulant, was 33. He had at least 2 sons with Ann Menis. He died in 1211, in his hometown, at the age of 38, and was buried in Chichester, West Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1173–1211":"1173–1211","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1171–1204":"1171–1204","1185–1280":"1185–1280","1211–1234":"1211–1234","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1139–1176":"1139–1176","1140–1173":"1140–1173","about 1170":"umbes 1170","1176":"1176","1185":"1185"